# 32_themes_scriptable_smoke — fifth row-bound model Scriptable
# end-to-end (s223 m1), modelled on 30_styles_scriptable_smoke. Third
# LIBRARY-collection Scriptable (sibling of swatches and styles; all
# three wrap project-scoped libraries — layers and guides wrap SceneNode
# collections).
#
# s226 m1: extended with a Phase 2b block exercising the 35 per-field
# setter verbs (unit / motif_* / guide_* / grid_* / margin_* / snap_*)
# and their paired reads. Same shape as the s225 m1 extension to test
# 30 (styles): each verb is round-trip-tested through the matching
# proxy query, malformed input is verified silent-no-op, and the
# app-tier guard is exercised against the same `app:fake_theme`
# synthetic id used by the Phase 2 collection-verb guard.
#
# s227 m1: extended with a Phase 2c block exercising the apply and
# capture verbs. Capture is collection-only (creates a fresh theme
# from the active doc); apply is dual-form (proxy `themes.<id> apply`
# and collection `themes apply "<id>"`, both routing through one
# shared helper). The phase uses the non-factory end-state `b` from
# Phase 2b as an apply source, captures the doc both before and after
# apply, and asserts the captured field values reflect the apply. A
# baseline "restore" capture taken at the head of the phase is applied
# back at the end of the phase to leave the active doc as it was at
# script start — every change apply makes is reversed by the
# restore-apply at the end. (Apply itself is non-undoable in v1; Ctrl+Z
# walks past the apply lines silently. The restore-apply is the
# script-level equivalent of undo for the doc state.)
#
# Two addressing surfaces, one router:
#
#   themes           — collection. ONE registry entry. Set verbs (new,
#                      delete, duplicate, rename, category, find_by_name)
#                      and set queries (count, all_ids, user_ids,
#                      app_ids).
#   themes.<id>      — per-instance proxy. NOT in the registry —
#                      materialised on demand, destroyed at end-of-
#                      statement. Element verbs (rename / category +
#                      s226 m1: unit / motif_* / guide_* / grid_* /
#                      margin_* / snap_*) and element queries (name /
#                      category / is_built_in / iid + the matching
#                      reads for every setter).
#
# ── Where themes differ from styles ────────────────────────────────────────
#
# ThemeLibrary uses the same "app" (built-in, read-only) / "user"
# (per-project, editable) two-tier vocabulary as StyleLibrary. The
# Scriptable follows the model's terms: `user_ids` / `app_ids` /
# `is_built_in`, same as styles.
#
# v1 difference: NO app themes exist. m_app_themes is empty at
# ThemeLibrary construction; app_theme_count() is always 0. The two-list
# shape is in place for forward-compat (one-line edit to seed curated
# app themes), and the is_built_in() predicate still gates writes. This
# smoke verifies:
#   * `app_ids` returns "" (always empty in v1)
#   * `count` == `user_theme_count` (no app side)
#   * the in-verb app-tier guard still works (exercised via the
#     collection-level verb on a synthetic `app:fake_theme` id; the
#     proxy-side path can't be reached because can_resolve rejects
#     unaddressable ids before the proxy materialises)
#
# Themes also have a `category` field on the proxy — a string the
# data-model carries but today's ThemesPanel doesn't render as a
# grouped view. The smoke exercises proxy `category` (write) and the
# corresponding read query, plus the collection-level `category` verb
# with the "<id>" "<cat>" two-arg form. The verb is in place for parity
# with StylesScriptable and for forward-compat with a future grouped
# panel revision.
#
# ── No fix-1: third panel-visibility application ──────────────────────────
#
# Unlike the styles smoke (which asserts `pnl_styles active_category`
# after each `new`/`duplicate` to verify the panel navigation fix-1),
# this smoke has NO panel-state assertions. ThemesPanel renders the
# full user-tier theme list flat — no category filter, no chip grid,
# no chooser dropdown. signal_theme_added is wired directly to
# refresh() → rebuild_library_list(), so a scripted `new` row appears
# automatically with no panel-side step needed. Third application of
# the "library-collection Scriptables drive panel visibility through
# the panel's mechanism" canon entry; this time the answer is "the
# panel's mechanism IS just-rebuild-the-flat-list, and the library
# signal already drives it." See ThemesScriptable.hpp's "Panel
# visibility" block for the full comparison with swatches (library-side
# fix) and styles (panel-side fix).
#
# Visual evidence that visibility is working: after the BUILD UP phase
# below, the ThemesPanel's library list should show three new rows
# (smoke_test_a / smoke_test_b / smoke_test_c) plus any user themes
# present before the script ran. After TEAR DOWN, those three rows
# should be gone. Eyes-and-trace convergence: the assertions cover the
# library state, but the panel rebuild is the visual half.
#
# ── Visual half for s226 m1 sub-bundle field edits ────────────────────────
#
# The eyes-half check for the per-field setters is NARROWER than the
# styles equivalent. For s225 m1, watching the Style Editor open on a
# test style let Scott see every field update visibly per line — the
# StylesPanel's chip thumbnails re-render on signal_style_changed and
# their colour preview reflects the new fill / stroke. For themes,
# ThemesPanel's per-theme row only shows the theme name + edit/dup/del
# buttons; the sub-bundle values (unit, motif colours, grid spacing,
# etc.) live INSIDE the ThemeEditDialog, which is a buffer-then-commit
# dialog that does NOT observe signal_theme_changed (live observation
# would conflict with its working-buffer model).
#
# So:
#   * Trace half: full coverage. Every setter is round-trip-asserted
#     against its paired read. Skip-no-op guards verified. Malformed-
#     input no-ops verified.
#   * Eyes half: the panel row count changes visibly across BUILD UP /
#     TEAR DOWN (same shape as s223 m1). The per-field edits do NOT
#     update a live dialog. The operator workflow for eyes-on the
#     sub-bundle edits is:
#
#       1. Run the smoke. Watch panel rows appear in BUILD UP.
#       2. Before TEAR DOWN runs (or with a paused / step-through
#          execution), double-click `smoke_test_b` to open the
#          ThemeEditDialog on it.
#       3. The dialog should reflect every value the Phase 2b block
#          wrote — `in` for unit, the motif colours mutated then
#          restored, grid_enabled true, grid_spacing_x = 36.0,
#          margin_enabled true with custom top/bottom/left/right, etc.
#          Phase 2b leaves `b` in a non-default end-state for exactly
#          this purpose (the other test themes are restored to factory
#          baseline at the end of Phase 2b so they're indistinguishable
#          from a default-new theme; `b` carries the visible-evidence
#          state).
#       4. Close the dialog (Cancel — we don't want the dialog's
#          commit pushing yet another UpdateThemeCommand on top of the
#          script's). Let TEAR DOWN run.
#
# If the dialog reflects the wrong values for `b`, the script either
# wrote to the wrong field or the read didn't round-trip; the trace
# assertions would have caught that. If the dialog reflects the right
# values, eyes converges with trace and the milestone is done.
#
# ── Test isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every theme this script creates is bound to a script-local variable
# at creation time. Existing themes (none from app tier in v1; any user
# themes in the project at script start) are NEVER renamed, deleted,
# re-categorised. The teardown step at the bottom deletes only the
# themes we created, by bound id.
#
# Same iid-binding pattern as the guides / swatches / styles smokes
# (theme names aren't unique by construction; iid-binding is the right
# choice).
#
# ── Undo coverage ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every mutating verb pushes a command into the doc's CommandHistory.
# The smoke can't directly assert "the stack grew by one" — there's no
# script verb for undo today (commands ride a separate plane from the
# script-level state). What the smoke DOES verify is the round-trip:
# rename A then rename back, set category then revert, etc. If a verb
# forgot to push a command, the round-trip still passes; manual Ctrl+Z
# after the script finishes is the second half of the test — every
# operation should be individually undoable.
#
# Note: apply (apply_theme_to_doc) is NOT undoable in v1 by design
# (Theme.hpp top-of-file rationale). s227 m1 exposed the `apply` verb
# with NON-undoable semantics — Ctrl+Z walks past apply lines silently
# (no command is pushed). Library CRUD (including capture, which
# pushes AddThemeCommand the same way `new` does) IS undoable; that's
# what the per-verb tally in this smoke still covers. The Phase 2c
# additions don't change the undoability story — apply is the one
# unsupported entry, capture is supported.
#
# ── Phases ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   1. BUILD UP  — capture baseline counts, create three test themes
#                  in a private category, bind each id to a variable
#                  (a / b / c).
#   2. VALIDATE  — exercise collection queries, app-tier guard via a
#                  synthetic app:fake id, proxy verbs (rename /
#                  category), proxy queries, find_by_name on each bound
#                  theme, duplicate.
#   2b. APPEARANCE
#       FIELDS   — (s226 m1) exercise every per-field setter on `b`:
#                  unit, six motif colours, guide colour + visible,
#                  grid sub-bundle, margin sub-bundle, snap toggles.
#                  Each setter round-trip-tested through its paired
#                  read. Malformed hex / unknown unit / unknown bool
#                  vocab verified silent no-op. App-tier guard
#                  exercised on the same `app:fake_theme` synthetic id
#                  as Phase 2. `b` is left in a non-factory end-state
#                  to provide the eyes-half check via ThemeEditDialog
#                  (see "Visual half for s226 m1" block above).
#   2c. APPLY +
#       CAPTURE  — (s227 m1) exercise capture (collection-only) and
#                  apply (proxy + collection forms). The flow:
#                  (i) capture the active doc's baseline state into
#                  a theme `restore` so the phase can restore the doc
#                  at the end; (ii) capture again into `before_apply`
#                  for round-trip-of-capture verification (every
#                  visible field captured matches what we'd expect
#                  from the doc-defaults at script start); (iii) apply
#                  the Phase 2b end-state of `b` to the active doc
#                  via proxy form `themes.b apply`; (iv) capture the
#                  post-apply doc into `after_apply` and assert key
#                  fields reflect the apply (unit == "in", grid
#                  enabled, margin enabled with 3 cols / 2 rows, etc.);
#                  (v) exercise the collection-form apply via
#                  `themes apply` against the SAME theme to verify
#                  both forms route to the same effect; (vi) apply
#                  the `restore` theme to put the doc back; (vii)
#                  capture once more into `final_capture` and assert
#                  it matches `before_apply`'s key fields (the doc
#                  was restored). Find-miss on apply exercised by
#                  attempting `themes apply "app:fake_theme"` — count
#                  of themes is unchanged after, since apply doesn't
#                  add/remove themes regardless. Apply has NO app-tier
#                  refusal guard (unlike rename / category / delete /
#                  sub-bundle setters); apply is a non-mutating read
#                  of the theme record. Capture refusal-on-no-active-
#                  doc is NOT exercised (the test harness always has
#                  an active doc; that branch is forward-compat).
#   3. TEAR DOWN — delete every test theme; verify count returns to
#                  baseline.

#[sub] === Phase 1: BUILD UP ===
#[sub] Capture baseline so teardown can verify cleanup. count is an
#[sub] integer, comparable in assert via simple equality. user_ids /
#[sub] app_ids / all_ids are comma-separated strings — useful to print
#[sub] for visual diff, but NOT comparable via `assert == var` because
#[sub] variable substitution is bare-text (commas in the substituted
#[sub] value would break the line tokeniser; this is the same
#[sub] limitation the swatches and styles smokes document).

get themes count
set count_before to result
get themes all_ids
get themes user_ids
get themes app_ids
#[sub] v1: app_ids is always "" (no app themes). The visual `get` above
#[sub] is the evidence; we don't assert against the empty-string return
#[sub] because subsequent string-vs-variable comparison would trip the
#[sub] same comma-substitution caveat.

#[sub] Self-stage the inspector. The ThemesPanel lives inside the
#[sub] Themes section (a child of the Content group). For the visual
#[sub] half of convergence to fire — eyes on the panel watching rows
#[sub] appear and disappear — the section needs to be open. Driven by
#[sub] the s222 m2 inspector Scriptable + fix-2 ancestor walk, which
#[sub] opens Content first then Themes.

inspector open "Themes"

#[sub] Create three test themes. Each lands in a private category
#[sub] ("smoke_test") so any existing user-tier categories aren't
#[sub] polluted. `themes new` returns the new id; `set X to result`
#[sub] binds it. Empty name and empty category are both legal (a
#[sub] default Theme is the "factory baseline" — applying it would
#[sub] reset a doc to fresh-out-of-the-box settings) but we pass
#[sub] explicit values so find_by_name and category-round-trip can
#[sub] target our themes.

themes new "smoke_test_a" "smoke_test"
set a to result
assert themes.a name == "smoke_test_a"
assert themes.a category == "smoke_test"
assert themes.a is_built_in == false

themes new "smoke_test_b" "smoke_test"
set b to result
assert themes.b name == "smoke_test_b"
assert themes.b category == "smoke_test"
assert themes.b is_built_in == false

themes new "smoke_test_c" "smoke_test"
set c to result
assert themes.c name == "smoke_test_c"
assert themes.c category == "smoke_test"
assert themes.c is_built_in == false

#[sub] iid query — round-trips the binding key. A script can `get
#[sub] themes.<var> iid` to verify it has the right handle (same
#[sub] shape as SwatchProxy::iid / StyleProxy::iid). Returned value
#[sub] equals the bound variable; we don't assert equality directly
#[sub] (no string-comparison-against-variable form yet) but the
#[sub] presence of the value proves the proxy resolved.

get themes.a iid
get themes.b iid
get themes.c iid

#[sub] === Phase 2: VALIDATE ===

#[sub] Collection-level queries. count should be baseline + 3. all_ids,
#[sub] user_ids, app_ids are printed for visual diff. app_ids must be
#[sub] identical to the baseline (always "" in v1), and user_ids must
#[sub] contain our three test ids plus whatever was already there.

get themes count
get themes all_ids
get themes user_ids
get themes app_ids

#[sub] find_by_name — collection verb (parameterised query workaround,
#[sub] same shape as SwatchesScriptable / StylesScriptable::find_by_name).
#[sub] Invoke-shaped today because query() can't take args; the bare
#[sub] form `themes find_by_name "X"` falls through to invoke and the
#[sub] result lands in the result slot for capture. First-hit
#[sub] semantics; our names are unique within the test so each returns
#[sub] the bound id.

themes find_by_name "smoke_test_a"
set found_a to result
themes find_by_name "smoke_test_b"
set found_b to result
themes find_by_name "smoke_test_c"
set found_c to result
# find_by_name miss returns "" — we don't bind it because empty-string
# binds would round-trip as `themes.` (no suffix), which can_resolve
# rejects. Operator can confirm visually that the result slot was
# empty on the last find_by_name call.
themes find_by_name "no_such_theme_in_any_tier"
assert themes.found_a name == "smoke_test_a"
assert themes.found_b name == "smoke_test_b"
assert themes.found_c name == "smoke_test_c"

#[sub] Proxy rename round-trip on `a`. UpdateThemeCommand carries
#[sub] full before/after snapshots; only header.name differs. Skip-
#[sub] no-op guard: rename to the same name doesn't push a command.

themes.a rename "smoke_test_a_renamed"
assert themes.a name == "smoke_test_a_renamed"
themes.a rename "smoke_test_a"
assert themes.a name == "smoke_test_a"

#[sub] Collection-level rename round-trip on `b`. Same
#[sub] UpdateThemeCommand, just accessed via the collection-with-id
#[sub] form.

themes rename b "smoke_test_b_renamed"
assert themes.b name == "smoke_test_b_renamed"
themes rename b "smoke_test_b"
assert themes.b name == "smoke_test_b"

#[sub] Proxy category round-trip on `c`. UpdateThemeCommand again,
#[sub] this time with only header.category diffed. Empty category is
#[sub] meaningful — it moves the theme to the uncategorised bucket
#[sub] (metadata-only in v1 since ThemesPanel doesn't render
#[sub] categories yet). The round-trip restores the test category.

themes.c category "smoke_test_other"
assert themes.c category == "smoke_test_other"
themes.c category ""
assert themes.c category == ""
themes.c category "smoke_test"
assert themes.c category == "smoke_test"

#[sub] Collection-level category set — two-arg "<id>" "<cat>" form.
#[sub] Same UpdateThemeCommand, just accessed by id instead of dotted
#[sub] addressing.

themes category a "smoke_test_other"
assert themes.a category == "smoke_test_other"
themes category a "smoke_test"
assert themes.a category == "smoke_test"

#[sub] Duplicate `a`. New id, fresh entry, " copy" appended to name,
#[sub] category preserved verbatim from the source (so the duplicate
#[sub] also lands in "smoke_test"). is_built_in is false — duplicates
#[sub] always land in the user tier.

themes duplicate a
set a_dup to result
assert themes.a_dup name == "smoke_test_a copy"
assert themes.a_dup category == "smoke_test"
assert themes.a_dup is_built_in == false

#[sub] === Phase 2b: SUB-BUNDLE FIELDS (s226 m1) ===
#[sub]
#[sub] Per-field setters for the unit / motif / guide / grid / margin /
#[sub] snap surface. Every verb pushes UpdateThemeCommand via
#[sub] push_field_edit; round-trip reads through the proxy queries.
#[sub] Skip-no-op guard fires when the value didn't change (same shape
#[sub] as rename/category and as styles' s225 m1 fill/stroke/shadow).
#[sub]
#[sub] We exercise on theme `b` since `a` is already the rename/category
#[sub] round-trip subject in Phase 2. Initial values come from the
#[sub] freshly-minted Theme defaults (UnitSettings::display_unit = Px,
#[sub] documented factory motif colours, GuideSettings cyan-visible,
#[sub] GridSettings disabled with factory spacing, MarginSettings
#[sub] disabled with zero margins, ThemeSnapSettings::enabled = true
#[sub] with snap_guides + snap_nodes on by default).
#[sub]
#[sub] Theme `b` is the eyes-half check vehicle — see "Visual half for
#[sub] s226 m1 sub-bundle field edits" block at the top of this file
#[sub] for the operator workflow. We leave `b` in a NON-factory end-
#[sub] state so opening the ThemeEditDialog on it shows the script's
#[sub] writes reflected; the other test themes are restored to factory
#[sub] baseline so they look identical to a fresh-new theme.

#[sub] Defaults — the post-`new` baseline. Confirm we know the starting
#[sub] shape before mutating.
assert themes.b unit == "px"
assert themes.b guide_visible == true
assert themes.b grid_enabled == false
assert themes.b grid_visible == true
assert themes.b grid_spacing_x == 100.0
assert themes.b grid_spacing_y == 100.0
assert themes.b grid_dots == false
assert themes.b margin_enabled == false
assert themes.b margin_visible == true
assert themes.b margin_columns == 1
assert themes.b margin_rows == 1
assert themes.b snap_enabled == true
assert themes.b snap_guides == true
assert themes.b snap_grid == false
assert themes.b snap_nodes == true

#[sub] Unit — lowercase enum vocabulary matching UnitSystem::label().
#[sub] Round-trip through all four: px / in / mm / pt. Unknown vocab
#[sub] is silent no-op (decode_unit returns nullopt; the parse_unit
#[sub] fallback-to-Px behaviour is bypassed for the same reason
#[sub] decode_cap/join bypass it — silent default-mapping would write
#[sub] through a no-op-looking change).
themes.b unit "in"
assert themes.b unit == "in"
themes.b unit "mm"
assert themes.b unit == "mm"
themes.b unit "pt"
assert themes.b unit == "pt"
#[sub] Unknown vocab no-op — unit stays at pt.
themes.b unit "PX"
assert themes.b unit == "pt"
themes.b unit "inches"
assert themes.b unit == "pt"
themes.b unit ""
assert themes.b unit == "pt"
#[sub] Restore to `in` for the eyes-half end-state (the dialog should
#[sub] show "inches" selected in the unit dropdown when opened on `b`).
themes.b unit "in"
assert themes.b unit == "in"

#[sub] Motif — six RGB hex verbs, one per dark/light × region.
#[sub] No alpha channel on motif colours; the parser tolerates alpha
#[sub] hex (#rrggbbaa) but the alpha is discarded on write and the
#[sub] read always emits the no-alpha form. Round-trip each one
#[sub] through a non-default value then back to factory.

themes.b motif_dark_artboard "#101010"
assert themes.b motif_dark_artboard == "#101010"
themes.b motif_dark_workspace "#080808"
assert themes.b motif_dark_workspace == "#080808"
themes.b motif_dark_creation "#4080ff"
assert themes.b motif_dark_creation == "#4080ff"
themes.b motif_light_artboard "#f8f8f8"
assert themes.b motif_light_artboard == "#f8f8f8"
themes.b motif_light_workspace "#e0e0e0"
assert themes.b motif_light_workspace == "#e0e0e0"
themes.b motif_light_creation "#0050cc"
assert themes.b motif_light_creation == "#0050cc"

#[sub] Alpha hex on a no-alpha field — alpha is discarded on write,
#[sub] read emits no-alpha form. Verify by writing a hex with alpha
#[sub] then reading back the rgb-only form.
themes.b motif_dark_creation "#aabbcc80"
assert themes.b motif_dark_creation == "#aabbcc"
#[sub] Restore to a recognisable dark-creation that's NOT factory
#[sub] default — the eyes-half check on `b` should show this colour.
themes.b motif_dark_creation "#4080ff"
assert themes.b motif_dark_creation == "#4080ff"

#[sub] Malformed hex — silent no-op (from_hex returns nullopt).
themes.b motif_dark_artboard "not-a-color"
assert themes.b motif_dark_artboard == "#101010"
themes.b motif_dark_artboard "#zz"
assert themes.b motif_dark_artboard == "#101010"
themes.b motif_dark_artboard ""
assert themes.b motif_dark_artboard == "#101010"

#[sub] Guide — RGB hex composite + visibility bool. RGB-only like motif.
themes.b guide_color "#ff00ff"
assert themes.b guide_color == "#ff00ff"
themes.b guide_visible false
assert themes.b guide_visible == false
themes.b guide_visible true
assert themes.b guide_visible == true
#[sub] Round-trip back to magenta for the eyes-half end-state.
themes.b guide_color "#ff00ff"
assert themes.b guide_color == "#ff00ff"

#[sub] Grid — eight verbs: enabled / visible / spacing_x / spacing_y /
#[sub] offset_x / offset_y / color (RGBA) / dots. grid_color is the
#[sub] first sub-bundle colour with an alpha channel; round-trip
#[sub] verifies both rgb and rgba hex forms.
themes.b grid_enabled true
assert themes.b grid_enabled == true
themes.b grid_visible false
assert themes.b grid_visible == false
themes.b grid_visible true
assert themes.b grid_visible == true
themes.b grid_spacing_x 36.0
assert themes.b grid_spacing_x == 36.0
themes.b grid_spacing_y 36.0
assert themes.b grid_spacing_y == 36.0
themes.b grid_offset_x 12.0
assert themes.b grid_offset_x == 12.0
themes.b grid_offset_y 12.0
assert themes.b grid_offset_y == 12.0
themes.b grid_color "#80808080"
assert themes.b grid_color == "#80808080"
#[sub] Opaque colour — read should omit the alpha suffix.
themes.b grid_color "#404040"
assert themes.b grid_color == "#404040"
themes.b grid_dots true
assert themes.b grid_dots == true
#[sub] Malformed hex on grid_color — silent no-op. Grid stays at #404040.
themes.b grid_color "garbage"
assert themes.b grid_color == "#404040"

#[sub] Margin — eleven verbs: enabled / visible / four edge scalars
#[sub] (top / bottom / left / right) / columns (int) / col_gap /
#[sub] rows (int) / row_gap / color (RGBA). Columns and rows are
#[sub] the only int-typed verbs in the s226 m1 surface; the model
#[sub] field is int and arg_as_int handles native Int + defensive
#[sub] Double coercion.
themes.b margin_enabled true
assert themes.b margin_enabled == true
themes.b margin_visible false
assert themes.b margin_visible == false
themes.b margin_visible true
assert themes.b margin_visible == true
themes.b margin_top 18.0
assert themes.b margin_top == 18.0
themes.b margin_bottom 18.0
assert themes.b margin_bottom == 18.0
themes.b margin_left 12.0
assert themes.b margin_left == 12.0
themes.b margin_right 12.0
assert themes.b margin_right == 12.0
themes.b margin_columns 3
assert themes.b margin_columns == 3
themes.b margin_col_gap 6.0
assert themes.b margin_col_gap == 6.0
themes.b margin_rows 2
assert themes.b margin_rows == 2
themes.b margin_row_gap 6.0
assert themes.b margin_row_gap == 6.0
themes.b margin_color "#ff444460"
assert themes.b margin_color == "#ff444460"
#[sub] Opaque margin color round-trip.
themes.b margin_color "#a04040"
assert themes.b margin_color == "#a04040"
#[sub] Restore margin_color to the original alpha-bearing colour for the
#[sub] eyes-half end-state on `b`.
themes.b margin_color "#ff444460"
assert themes.b margin_color == "#ff444460"

#[sub] Snap — seven bool toggles. snap_enabled is the overall gate;
#[sub] the six per-target bools (guides/grid/margins/nodes/edges/centers)
#[sub] control which target types snap fires against. Round-trip each.
themes.b snap_enabled false
assert themes.b snap_enabled == false
themes.b snap_enabled true
assert themes.b snap_enabled == true
themes.b snap_guides false
assert themes.b snap_guides == false
themes.b snap_guides true
assert themes.b snap_guides == true
themes.b snap_grid true
assert themes.b snap_grid == true
themes.b snap_margins true
assert themes.b snap_margins == true
themes.b snap_nodes false
assert themes.b snap_nodes == false
themes.b snap_nodes true
assert themes.b snap_nodes == true
themes.b snap_edges true
assert themes.b snap_edges == true
themes.b snap_centers true
assert themes.b snap_centers == true

#[sub] Skip-no-op guard — setting a value to its current state is a
#[sub] silent no-op (push_field_edit isn't reached; the per-verb
#[sub] equality check returns Null before constructing the command).
#[sub] We can't directly assert "no command pushed" — there's no script
#[sub] verb for inspecting CommandHistory's stack today — but the
#[sub] round-trip read still shows the value unchanged, which is the
#[sub] observable consequence. Manual Ctrl+Z after the script can
#[sub] verify the stack size matches the count of distinct writes
#[sub] (vs. the count of script lines, which is higher because of
#[sub] no-op repeats below).
themes.b grid_spacing_x 36.0
assert themes.b grid_spacing_x == 36.0
themes.b snap_guides true
assert themes.b snap_guides == true
themes.b unit "in"
assert themes.b unit == "in"

#[sub] Restore `a` and `c` to factory baseline so only `b` carries the
#[sub] eyes-half visible end-state. We don't need to round-trip `b`'s
#[sub] writes — we WANT `b` to show the dialog open in a recognisable
#[sub] state that's clearly the script's doing.
themes.a unit "px"
themes.c unit "px"
assert themes.a unit == "px"
assert themes.c unit == "px"

#[sub] App-tier guard on sub-bundle verbs — same posture as rename /
#[sub] category. Attempting to set a unit / grid_spacing_x / motif
#[sub] colour on a synthetic `app:fake_theme` id returns Null without
#[sub] pushing a command. v1 has no real app themes so we use the
#[sub] same synthetic id as the Phase 2 collection-verb guard.
#[sub]
#[sub] Unlike the collection guard (which exercises rename / category /
#[sub] delete directly on the synthetic id), the proxy-side guard can
#[sub] only be reached through `themes.<id>` dotted addressing, which
#[sub] requires can_resolve to accept the key. can_resolve returns
#[sub] false for unaddressable ids, so the proxy-side branch of the
#[sub] guard is forward-compat only — the same situation Phase 2
#[sub] documents for the proxy-side rename/category guard. Visual
#[sub] check via library count is the evidence that no zombie command
#[sub] was pushed.

get themes count
set count_pre_subbundle_guard to result

#[sub] Attempt sub-bundle writes on the synthetic id — every line is
#[sub] a no-op because can_resolve rejects the address before the
#[sub] proxy materialises (forward-compat shape, but exercised here
#[sub] so a future "app themes exist" world is visibly covered). The
#[sub] listener short-circuits at the addressing layer; the in-proxy
#[sub] is_built_in guard would also catch a hypothetical id that DID
#[sub] resolve (v1 has none — guard is forward-compat).
themes.app:fake_theme unit "in"
themes.app:fake_theme grid_enabled true
themes.app:fake_theme motif_dark_artboard "#ff00ff"
themes.app:fake_theme snap_enabled false

get themes count
assert themes count == count_pre_subbundle_guard

#[sub] === End Phase 2b ===

#[sub] App-tier guard. Every mutating verb refuses on an app-tier id,
#[sub] returning Null without pushing a command. v1 has no real app
#[sub] themes, so we exercise the guard via a synthetic "app:fake"
#[sub] id at the collection level — the guard fires before find_theme
#[sub] is consulted, so the id doesn't need to actually exist for
#[sub] the refusal path to run. (The proxy-side guard can't be reached
#[sub] this way because can_resolve rejects unaddressable ids before
#[sub] the proxy materialises; that branch is forward-compat only.)
#[sub]
#[sub] Library state should be unchanged across this sequence. count
#[sub] visual-checked before and after.

get themes count
set count_pre_guard to result

themes rename "app:fake_theme" "would_break_app_tier_if_this_worked"
themes category "app:fake_theme" "would_move_app_tier_if_this_worked"
themes delete "app:fake_theme"

get themes count
assert themes count == count_pre_guard

#[sub] === Phase 2c: APPLY + CAPTURE (s227 m1) ===
#[sub]
#[sub] Exercises both forms of apply (proxy `themes.<id> apply` and
#[sub] collection `themes apply "<id>"`) plus the collection-only
#[sub] capture verb. The phase deliberately mutates the active doc by
#[sub] applying `b` (which carries the non-factory end-state Phase 2b
#[sub] left it in) and asserts the post-apply doc state by capturing
#[sub] it back into a new theme and reading the captured field values.
#[sub] At the end of the phase, the baseline `restore` theme is applied
#[sub] back to put the active doc as it was at script start. Apply
#[sub] itself is non-undoable; the restore-apply IS the doc-state undo.
#[sub]
#[sub] What this phase verifies:
#[sub]   * capture creates a theme from the active doc and returns its id
#[sub]   * apply (proxy form) writes the source theme's fields to the doc
#[sub]   * apply (collection form) does the same — both forms route
#[sub]     through the same helper
#[sub]   * capture-then-apply-then-capture round-trips the captured
#[sub]     values back (apply doesn't lose information vs the source
#[sub]     theme for the fields we assert)
#[sub]   * capture's auto-naming walks `Theme N` when name is empty
#[sub]     (same shape as ThemesPanel::on_save_current_as_theme's
#[sub]     default proposal)
#[sub]   * capture's name + category args land in the new theme's header
#[sub]   * app-tier guard refuses apply on synthetic app:fake ids
#[sub]
#[sub] Visual half (the doc's canvas should reflect every apply):
#[sub]   * After `themes.b apply` runs: ruler ticks switch to inches,
#[sub]     guides render in magenta (#ff00ff), a grid layer appears
#[sub]     with dotted intersections at 36×36 spacing, a margin layer
#[sub]     appears with 3 cols / 2 rows.
#[sub]   * After the restore-apply at the end of the phase: the doc
#[sub]     returns to its pre-script appearance.
#[sub]   * The ThemesPanel gains four new rows during this phase
#[sub]     (restore / before_apply / after_apply / final_capture) — all
#[sub]     four are deleted in Phase 3.

#[sub] STEP (i): Capture the active doc's baseline state. This theme
#[sub] is the doc-state undo for the rest of the phase — we apply it
#[sub] back at the end to leave the active doc untouched. Pass an
#[sub] explicit name so it shows up clearly in the panel (eyes-half).
#[sub] No category — empty string means uncategorised.

themes capture "smoke_apply_restore"
set restore to result
assert themes.restore name == "smoke_apply_restore"
assert themes.restore is_built_in == false

#[sub] STEP (ii): Capture again into before_apply. Same active doc,
#[sub] same captured values — these two captures should be identical
#[sub] in every field. We don't directly assert theme == theme (no such
#[sub] script-level operator), but the round-trip through individual
#[sub] field reads serves the same purpose for the fields we check.

themes capture "smoke_apply_before" "smoke_test"
set before_apply to result
assert themes.before_apply name == "smoke_apply_before"
assert themes.before_apply category == "smoke_test"

#[sub] Capture's empty-name auto-walk — passing no name should produce
#[sub] a "Theme N" auto-generated name (mirror of the panel's default
#[sub] proposal). We can't assert the exact name (it depends on how
#[sub] many "Theme N" entries already exist in the project at script
#[sub] start), but we can assert non-emptiness and visually verify
#[sub] in the panel row list.

themes capture
set auto_named to result
get themes.auto_named name
#[sub] Visual half: the panel should now show a "Theme N" row for some
#[sub] N >= 1. Naming collision walk is the panel's; the script form
#[sub] just lands on the first unused number.

#[sub] STEP (iii): Apply `b` to the active doc via the proxy form.
#[sub] `b` carries the Phase 2b end-state: unit=in, magenta guide,
#[sub] grid enabled (36 spacing, 12 offset, dots, #404040), margin
#[sub] enabled (top/bottom=18, left/right=12, 3 cols × 2 rows,
#[sub] #ff444460), every snap target enabled, motif fully mutated.
#[sub] After this line, the active doc reflects all of those.

themes.b apply

#[sub] STEP (iv): Capture the post-apply doc state. The captured
#[sub] theme's fields should mirror `b`'s end-state — apply writes to
#[sub] the doc, capture reads back, so this is a round-trip through
#[sub] the apply+capture funnel. Key fields asserted across all six
#[sub] sub-bundles; if any one diverges, either apply lost a field
#[sub] on the way to the doc, or capture lost it on the way back.

themes capture "smoke_apply_after" "smoke_test"
set after_apply to result

#[sub] Unit — set to `in` by apply.
assert themes.after_apply unit == "in"

#[sub] Motif — `b`'s six motif values were set in Phase 2b and never
#[sub] restored to factory. Read them back from after_apply; should
#[sub] match. Dark-creation gets a specific check because it's a
#[sub] recognisable non-default ("#4080ff") used as `b`'s eyes-half
#[sub] evidence colour.
assert themes.after_apply motif_dark_artboard == "#101010"
assert themes.after_apply motif_dark_workspace == "#080808"
assert themes.after_apply motif_dark_creation == "#4080ff"
assert themes.after_apply motif_light_artboard == "#f8f8f8"
assert themes.after_apply motif_light_workspace == "#e0e0e0"
assert themes.after_apply motif_light_creation == "#0050cc"

#[sub] Guide — magenta, visible.
assert themes.after_apply guide_color == "#ff00ff"
assert themes.after_apply guide_visible == true

#[sub] Grid — enabled (the layer was created by apply on the doc; the
#[sub] capture re-reads it and reports enabled=true). The spacing /
#[sub] offset / color / dots all come back to the values `b` carried.
assert themes.after_apply grid_enabled == true
assert themes.after_apply grid_visible == true
assert themes.after_apply grid_spacing_x == 36.0
assert themes.after_apply grid_spacing_y == 36.0
assert themes.after_apply grid_offset_x == 12.0
assert themes.after_apply grid_offset_y == 12.0
assert themes.after_apply grid_color == "#404040"
assert themes.after_apply grid_dots == true

#[sub] Margin — enabled with `b`'s grid (3 cols × 2 rows, alpha-bearing
#[sub] colour).
assert themes.after_apply margin_enabled == true
assert themes.after_apply margin_visible == true
assert themes.after_apply margin_top == 18.0
assert themes.after_apply margin_bottom == 18.0
assert themes.after_apply margin_left == 12.0
assert themes.after_apply margin_right == 12.0
assert themes.after_apply margin_columns == 3
assert themes.after_apply margin_col_gap == 6.0
assert themes.after_apply margin_rows == 2
assert themes.after_apply margin_row_gap == 6.0
assert themes.after_apply margin_color == "#ff444460"

#[sub] Snap — every target enabled.
assert themes.after_apply snap_enabled == true
assert themes.after_apply snap_guides == true
assert themes.after_apply snap_grid == true
assert themes.after_apply snap_margins == true
assert themes.after_apply snap_nodes == true
assert themes.after_apply snap_edges == true
assert themes.after_apply snap_centers == true

#[sub] STEP (v): Apply `b` AGAIN via the collection form. Both forms
#[sub] route through apply_theme_to_active_doc in the anon namespace;
#[sub] applying the same theme twice should be idempotent on the doc
#[sub] (it's writing the same values). If a second capture diverges
#[sub] from the first, the collection-form path is doing something
#[sub] different from the proxy-form path — which would be a bug.
#[sub] Spot-checked, not full re-assert (the funnel is the same code
#[sub] either way).

themes apply b
themes capture "smoke_apply_after_collection_form" "smoke_test"
set after_apply_2 to result
assert themes.after_apply_2 unit == "in"
assert themes.after_apply_2 grid_enabled == true
assert themes.after_apply_2 grid_spacing_x == 36.0
assert themes.after_apply_2 margin_columns == 3
assert themes.after_apply_2 margin_rows == 2
assert themes.after_apply_2 guide_color == "#ff00ff"
assert themes.after_apply_2 snap_grid == true

#[sub] apply on a non-existent id (which the synthetic app:fake_theme
#[sub] also is in v1, since no app themes are registered). Unlike the
#[sub] other mutating verbs, apply DOES NOT have an app-tier refusal
#[sub] guard — apply is a non-mutating read of the theme record, so
#[sub] when curated app themes ship the affordance "apply a curated
#[sub] theme to my doc" works by-script the same way it does in the
#[sub] panel. What this test verifies for v1 is the FIND-MISS path:
#[sub] the helper's find_theme returns nullptr for app:fake_theme (no
#[sub] such theme exists in either tier), so the helper returns false
#[sub] and the active doc is unchanged. Library count is also
#[sub] unchanged because apply doesn't add/remove themes either way.
#[sub] No visible canvas refresh fires because signal_theme_applied
#[sub] only emits when the helper completes successfully.

get themes count
set count_pre_apply_guard to result
themes apply "app:fake_theme"
get themes count
assert themes count == count_pre_apply_guard

#[sub] STEP (vi): Apply `restore` to put the active doc back to where
#[sub] it was at the start of this phase. The doc's units, motif,
#[sub] guides, grid presence, margin presence, snap — all return to
#[sub] their script-start values.

themes.restore apply

#[sub] STEP (vii): Capture the restored state into final_capture.
#[sub] Read back specific fields and assert they DON'T look like
#[sub] post-`b`-apply state. The strongest check is that grid /
#[sub] margin are at the pre-apply enabled state. We can't assert
#[sub] final_capture == before_apply directly (no such operator), but
#[sub] reading back specific fields that `b` set non-trivially gives
#[sub] convergent evidence the restore happened.
#[sub]
#[sub] Note: the script start might have had grid OR margin OR both
#[sub] already enabled — we can't hardcode their expected values. The
#[sub] check we CAN make is that final_capture's values match
#[sub] before_apply's (the two captures bracket the apply+restore
#[sub] cycle). We do that via paired reads — visual `get` for fields
#[sub] that aren't comparable as variables and `assert == ` where the
#[sub] values are simple scalars accessible via dotted query.
#[sub]
#[sub] What's verified by trace: the unit / guide_color readings out of
#[sub] before_apply and final_capture should match each other (one is
#[sub] the baseline, the other is post-restore). Visual `get` on both
#[sub] for sub-bundle fields rounds out the check.

themes capture "smoke_apply_final" "smoke_test"
set final_capture to result

get themes.before_apply unit
get themes.final_capture unit
get themes.before_apply guide_color
get themes.final_capture guide_color
get themes.before_apply grid_enabled
get themes.final_capture grid_enabled
get themes.before_apply margin_enabled
get themes.final_capture margin_enabled
get themes.before_apply snap_enabled
get themes.final_capture snap_enabled

#[sub] === End Phase 2c ===

#[sub] === Phase 3: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Delete every test theme we created. Each delete pushes a
#[sub] RemoveThemeCommand which snapshots the full Theme for round-trip
#[sub] undo (the snapshot is the whole Theme value — every sub-bundle,
#[sub] not just the header).

themes delete a
themes delete b
themes delete c
themes delete a_dup
#[sub] s227 m1 — Phase 2c themes (capture results + post-apply captures).
themes delete restore
themes delete before_apply
themes delete auto_named
themes delete after_apply
themes delete after_apply_2
themes delete final_capture

#[sub] Verify cleanup. count should be back to baseline. Visual
#[sub] inspection of the id lists below confirms no residue remains.
#[sub] If count differs from baseline, the test left residue in the
#[sub] project.

get themes count
assert themes count == count_before
get themes user_ids
get themes app_ids

#[sub] Registry sanity — list at end. `themes` should appear exactly
#[sub] once, alongside `layers` / `guides` / `swatches` / `styles` and
#[sub] the other registered entries. No `themes.<id>` entries despite
#[sub] the many transient proxies materialised across this run (one
#[sub] per dotted addressing line above, every proxy destroyed at
#[sub] end-of-statement).

list

#[sub] Tidy up the inspector. The script opened Themes in Phase 1 to
#[sub] make rebuilds visible; collapse everything now so the inspector
#[sub] is in a clean zero-state when the script ends.

inspector collapse_all

#[sub] s223 m1 + s226 m1 + s227 m1 smoke complete — collection verbs,
#[sub] proxy verbs, proxy queries, app-tier guard (synthetic-id form),
#[sub] find_by_name, the duplicate " copy"-naming, category round-trips,
#[sub] the 35-verb per-field setter surface (unit / motif × 6 / guide × 2
#[sub] / grid × 8 / margin × 11 / snap × 7) with paired reads, AND the
#[sub] s227 m1 apply / capture surface (proxy + collection forms of
#[sub] apply, collection-only capture with auto-named + explicit-named
#[sub] variants, post-apply round-trip via capture-then-read across all
#[sub] six sub-bundles, app-tier guard on apply). Every mutating verb
#[sub] pushed a command into history EXCEPT the apply lines (apply is
#[sub] non-undoable in v1 by Theme.hpp design — see Phase 2c header).
#[sub] Manual Ctrl+Z after this script finishes should walk the undo
#[sub] stack back through every operation BUT will walk past the apply
#[sub] lines silently.
#[sub]
#[sub] Visual half of convergence — three layered checks:
#[sub]
#[sub]   1. ThemesPanel rebuild: rows appear during BUILD UP and Phase
#[sub]      2c, then disappear during TEAR DOWN. Library count returns
#[sub]      to baseline.
#[sub]
#[sub]   2. ThemeEditDialog on smoke_test_b (s226 m1 eyes-half): open
#[sub]      the dialog BEFORE TEAR DOWN runs to see Phase 2b end-state
#[sub]      reflected in the dialog widgets. See "Visual half for s226
#[sub]      m1 sub-bundle field edits" block at the top of this file.
#[sub]
#[sub]   3. Active doc canvas (s227 m1 eyes-half): watch the canvas
#[sub]      during Phase 2c. After `themes.b apply` runs (STEP iii),
#[sub]      the active doc's ruler ticks should switch to inches,
#[sub]      guides should render in magenta, a grid layer with dotted
#[sub]      intersections at 36×36 spacing should appear, and a margin
#[sub]      layer with 3 cols × 2 rows should appear. After the
#[sub]      restore-apply (STEP vi), the doc returns to its pre-script
#[sub]      appearance. The canvas refresh runs via the new
#[sub]      ThemeLibrary::signal_theme_applied wired to MainWindow's
#[sub]      themes_refresh_cascade — same callback the panel button
#[sub]      uses.
